TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Determinants of Executive Compensation in Family-Controlled Public Corporations
AU  - Gomez-Mejia, Luis R.
AU  - Larraza-Kintana, Martin
AU  - Makri, Marianna
Y1  - 2003/04/01
PY  - 2003
DA  - 2003/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/30040616
DO  - 10.5465/30040616
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 226
EP  - 237
VL  - 46
IS  - 2
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Family-member CEOs of family-controlled firms receive lower total income than outsider CEOs, increasingly so as family ownership concentration increases. At the same time, their pay tends to be more insulated from risk and more sensitive to systematic (less controllable) business risk. The presence of institutional investors and R&D intensity play important moderating roles in these relationships.
AB  - Family-member CEOs of family-controlled firms receive lower total income than outsider CEOs, increasingly so as family ownership concentration increases. At the same time, their pay tends to be more insulated from risk and more sensitive to systematic (less controllable) business risk. The presence of institutional investors and R&D intensity play important moderating roles in these relationships.
SN  - 0001-4273
M3  - doi: 10.5465/30040616
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/30040616
Y2  - 2026/04/24
